    <subsection>
        <title>Factoring Trinomials by Generic Rectangles</title>

        <p>In <xref ref="section-multiplying-polynomials">Section</xref>, we learned how to multiply binomials with generic rectangles. The following generic rectangles are used to multiply <m>(y+5)(y-8)</m>:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Multiplying <m>(y+5)(y-8)</m> with Generic Rectangles</caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                        \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                        \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                        \draw (2,4.5) node {$y$};
                        \draw (4,4.5) node {$5$};
                        \draw (0.5,3) node {$y$};
                        \draw (0.5,1) node {$-8$};
                        \draw (2,3) node {$y^2$};
                        \draw (4,3) node {$5y$};
                        \draw (2,1) node {$-8y$};
                        \draw (4,1) node {$-40$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>The sum of those generic rectangles' area gives the product of <m>(y+5)(y-8)</m>:<md>
            <mrow>(y+5)(y-8)\amp=y^2+5y-8y-40</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=y^2-3y-40</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>To factor <m>y^2-3y-40</m> with generic rectangles, we put the first term <m>y^2</m> and the third term <m>-40</m> into the top left and bottom right boxes, and we have:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Setting up Generic Rectangles to Factor <m>y^2-3y-40</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                        \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                        \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                        \draw (2,3) node {$y^2$};
                        \draw (4,1) node {$-40$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Next, we mark the base and height of the top left rectangle. To make its area <m>y^2</m>, the only choice we have for its base and height is <m>y\cdot y=y^2</m>. Now the rectangles look like:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Marking the Top Left Rectangle's Base and Height</caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                        \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                        \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                        \draw (2,4.5) node {$y$};
                        \draw (0.5,3) node {$y$};
                        \draw (2,3) node {$y^2$};
                        \draw (4,1) node {$-40$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Next, our task is to come up with the base and height of the bottom right rectangle. Since the area of the rectangle is <m>-40</m>, the product of its base and height must be <m>-40</m>. According to <xref ref="table-factor-pair-of-negative-forty">Table</xref>, we will try each pair in the list. For example, if we try <m>-5</m> and <m>8</m>, the rectangles would look like:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Trying <m>y-5</m> and <m>y+8</m> as Factors of <m>y^2-3y-40</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                        \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                        \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                        \draw (2,4.5) node {$y$};
                        \draw (4,4.5) node {$-5$};
                        \draw (0.5,3) node {$y$};
                        \draw (0.5,1) node {$8$};
                        \draw (2,3) node {$y^2$};
                        \draw (4,3) node {$-5y$};
                        \draw (2,1) node {$8y$};
                        \draw (4,1) node {$-40$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>The sum of those rectangles' area is <m>y^2-5y+8y-40=y^2+3y-40</m>, which is different from <m>y^2-3y-40</m>. To make the area match the given trinomial, we try the pair <m>5</m> and <m>-8</m>, and we have:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Trying <m>y+5</m> and <m>y-8</m> as Factors of <m>y^2-3y-40</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                        \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                        \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                        \draw (2,4.5) node {$y$};
                        \draw (4,4.5) node {$5$};
                        \draw (0.5,3) node {$y$};
                        \draw (0.5,1) node {$-8$};
                        \draw (2,3) node {$y^2$};
                        \draw (4,3) node {$5y$};
                        \draw (2,1) node {$-8y$};
                        \draw (4,1) node {$-40$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Now, the sum of those generic rectangles is <m>y^2-3y-40</m>, matching the given trinomial. Dimensions of those generic rectangles show the solution<me>y^2-3y-40=(y+5)(y-8)</me></p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>m^2-mn-12n^2</m> with generic rectangles.</p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>We set up generic rectangles by putting the first and third terms into the corresponding places:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Setting up Generic Rectangles to Factor <m>m^2-mn-12n^2</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,3) node {$m^2$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$-12n^2$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Next, we mark each rectangle's base and height by guess-and-check. The top left rectangle's base and height must be <m>m</m>, as <m>m\cdot m=m^2</m>. To find the bottom right rectangle's dimensions, we list all factor pairs of <m>-12</m>:</p>

                <table>
                    <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>-12</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1\cdot(-12)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-11</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1)\cdot12</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>11</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2\cdot(-6)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2)\cdot6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>3\cdot(-4)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-3)\cdot4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>4\cdot(-3)</m></cell>
                            <cell>...</cell>
                            <cell>...</cell>
                            <cell>...</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>We try different factor pairs of <m>-12</m> for the bottom right rectangle's base and height until those rectangles' area adds up to <m>m^2-mn-12n^2</m>:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Factoring <m>m^2-mn-12n^2</m> with Generic Rectangles</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,4.5) node {$m$};
                                \draw (4,4.5) node {$3n$};
                                \draw (0.5,3) node {$m$};
                                \draw (0.5,1) node {$-4n$};
                                \draw (2,3) node {$m^2$};
                                \draw (4,3) node {$3mn$};
                                \draw (2,1) node {$-4mn$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$-12n^2$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Dimensions of those generic rectangles show the solution<me>m^2-mn-12n^2=(m+3n)(m-4n)</me></p>

            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Again, to factor trinomials <m>ax^2+bx+c</m> when <m>a=1</m>, the AC Method and Generic Rectangles Method are not as efficient as Listing Factor Pairs Method. They will be useful when we factor trinomials when <m>a\ne1</m> in later sections.</p>

